{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A pathogen slips into your bloodstream—maybe through a cut or inhaled in droplets. Your body doesn't recognize it yet. But scattered throughout your blood, white blood cells patrol like security guards, constantly scanning for anything unfamiliar.",
      "title": "The Intruder Arrives"
    },
    {
      "text": "A patrolling white blood cell encounters the invader and immediately raises an alarm. It processes what it sees, identifying the pathogen's unique molecular shape, then signals to other immune cells: \"We have a threat. Here's what to look for.\"",
      "title": "Alarm Bells Sound"
    },
    {
      "text": "That initial alert triggers your immune system to wake up. Immune cells gather intelligence, multiplying rapidly and preparing for action. Meanwhile, your bone marrow and thymus begin churning out specialized defenders tailored to attack this specific invader.",
      "title": "The Army Mobilizes"
    },
    {
      "text": "B cells receive the pathogen's blueprint and start mass-producing antibodies—thousands per second. These Y-shaped proteins flood your bloodstream like search-and-capture nets, each one designed to latch onto that specific pathogen.",
      "title": "Antibody Factory Activates"
    },
    {
      "text": "Watch as antibodies swarm the pathogens, binding to them like handcuffs. Everywhere an antibody clamps on, it sends a signal: \"Destroy this.\" The pathogen becomes tagged, marked, visible to killer cells that were waiting for exactly this signal.",
      "title": "Pathogens Get Tagged"
    },
    {
      "text": "Killer white blood cells (cytotoxic T cells) recognize the tagged invaders and attack. They rupture the pathogen's membrane, triggering it to burst and die. Simultaneously, macrophages engulf the debris like cleanup crews, removing dead pathogens from circulation.",
      "title": "The Attack Begins"
    },
    {
      "text": "As pathogens disappear and the threat recedes, most immune defenders scale back. But something remarkable happens: a few B cells and T cells transform into memory cells—veterans that embed themselves in your tissues, prepared to respond instantly if this same pathogen ever returns.",
      "title": "Victory and Memory"
    },
    {
      "text": "Weeks or months later, if the same pathogen appears again, memory cells recognize it instantly. They skip all the setup steps and launch a faster, stronger response. What once took days now happens in hours—you may never even feel sick.",
      "title": "The Rematch Advantage"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A promoter sequence sits quietly on the DNA strand like a landing pad. When RNA polymerase bumps into it, recognition happens instantly — the enzyme locks onto this start signal and positions itself perfectly to begin its reading journey down the DNA template.",
      "title": "RNA Polymerase Finds Its Start"
    },
    {
      "text": "The enzyme unzips the DNA double helix, separating the two strands like opening a zipper. One strand becomes the template — the one the enzyme will read. The other strand waits temporarily on the sidelines as transcription begins.",
      "title": "The DNA Helix Unwinds"
    },
    {
      "text": "As RNA polymerase moves along the template strand, it 'reads' each DNA base and grabs the matching nucleotide from the cellular soup around it. A pairs with U, T pairs with A, G pairs with C, C pairs with G — a rapid-fire matching game happening in real time.",
      "title": "Bases Match and Bond"
    },
    {
      "text": "Each nucleotide snaps into place, forming chemical bonds with its neighbor. The growing RNA strand extends like a chain being built one link at a time, stretching behind the moving enzyme as it continues reading forward along the DNA.",
      "title": "The RNA Chain Grows"
    },
    {
      "text": "RNA polymerase motors forward, reading base after base, pulling fresh nucleotides into place and extending the RNA chain. The enzyme never stops — it's a tireless reader, processing hundreds of bases per second in a smooth, continuous motion.",
      "title": "The Engine Keeps Running"
    },
    {
      "text": "Finally, RNA polymerase encounters a stop signal — a terminator sequence on the DNA. It's the red light after the green. The enzyme releases its grip, the newly made RNA peels away from the DNA template, and the two DNA strands zip back together.",
      "title": "Transcription Hits Stop"
    },
    {
      "text": "The finished RNA molecule — now called messenger RNA — floats free in the cell. It's a temporary copy of the genetic instructions, ready to leave the nucleus and deliver its message to protein-making machinery elsewhere in the cell.",
      "title": "The Message Leaves the Factory"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Your browser interprets your action—typing a URL or clicking a link—and packages it as an HTTP request. Think of it like drafting a letter with your address, the destination address, and what you're asking for. The request sits ready to travel.",
      "title": "The Trigger: Browser Prepares"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your browser connects to the server at the address you provided. This handshake is like calling ahead before sending your mail—both sides confirm they're ready to communicate. The connection opens the channel for your request to travel.",
      "title": "Dialing the Server"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your request travels across the internet through routers, cables, and networks—like a postal truck moving through cities and towns. It's heading toward the specific server that handles that domain, following the address you gave it.",
      "title": "The Request Travels"
    },
    {
      "text": "The server receives your packaged request and examines it. It reads what you're asking for, checks the path you specified, and determines which resource (webpage, image, data) you want. The server now knows its job.",
      "title": "Server Receives and Reads"
    },
    {
      "text": "Based on your request method and path, the server processes your ask. If you asked for data, it retrieves it. If you sent data to POST, it processes it. The server does the actual work—fetching files, querying databases, running logic—all behind the scenes.",
      "title": "Server Does the Work"
    },
    {
      "text": "The server assembles a response: the resource you asked for (webpage HTML, image bytes, JSON data) bundled with metadata about what it's sending back. Think of it as packing a box with the item you ordered plus a packing slip describing what's inside.",
      "title": "Server Builds the Response"
    },
    {
      "text": "The response travels the return journey across the internet, following the path back to your browser's address. Like a return shipment, it retraces the route through networks and routers until it reaches your machine.",
      "title": "Response Travels Back"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your browser receives the response package and checks the status code—did the request succeed (200), fail (404), or encounter an error (500)? This code tells your browser whether to proceed with displaying content or show an error message instead.",
      "title": "Browser Reads the Verdict"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the response is successful, your browser interprets the content. For HTML, it parses the structure. For images, it renders them. For JSON, it processes the data. Your browser transforms the response into something you can see and interact with.",
      "title": "Browser Renders the Result"
    },
    {
      "text": "As your browser displays the page, it notices additional resources referenced—stylesheets, images, scripts. For each one, a new HTTP request cycle begins. Your browser fires off multiple parallel requests, each following the same journey: send, wait, receive, process.",
      "title": "Chain Reaction: More Requests"
    },
    {
      "text": "The complete request-response cycle finishes when all content loads and your browser displays the final page. You see the result of every HTTP transaction stacked together—text, images, styling, interactivity—as one seamless webpage.",
      "title": "The Full Picture Appears"
    },
    {
      "text": "Behind the scenes, your browser and server can encounter hiccups. If the server doesn't respond in time, the request times out. If the path is wrong, the server returns 404. If the server crashes, it returns 500. Each failure triggers the response cycle just the same—you get notified of what went wrong.",
      "title": "When Things Go Wrong"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Your program starts running, and variables pile up on the stack and heap. Some objects get referenced by your code, others get abandoned midway. The garbage collector watches silently, waiting for the right moment to clean house.",
      "title": "The Memory Pile Accumulates"
    },
    {
      "text": "When memory runs low or a specific event triggers collection, the garbage collector springs into action. It pauses your program momentarily and says, \"Time to see what's still actually being used.\"",
      "title": "Collection Phase Begins"
    },
    {
      "text": "The collector starts at every GC root — local variables on the stack, global objects, anything your code is actively holding onto. These are the anchors; everything reachable from them is marked as alive.",
      "title": "Marking Starts from the Roots"
    },
    {
      "text": "From each root, the collector follows the chain of references like breadcrumbs through a forest. It moves from object to object: \"This object references that one, which references another.\" Each gets marked as visited.",
      "title": "Following Reference Chains"
    },
    {
      "text": "As the collector traces paths, some objects appear nowhere in any chain. Nobody references them. Nobody's code can reach them. These orphaned objects get marked as dead — eligible for reclamation.",
      "title": "Orphaned Objects Emerge"
    },
    {
      "text": "Once all reachable objects are marked and unreachable ones identified, the collector sweeps through memory. It deallocates the dead objects, compacts remaining ones, and reclaims their space back to the heap.",
      "title": "Sweeping Reclaims Space"
    },
    {
      "text": "With cleanup complete, your program resumes execution. The freed memory is now available for new objects. The cycle remains ready to repeat whenever memory pressure returns.",
      "title": "Program Resumes with Fresh Space"
    },
    {
      "text": "If a chain of dead objects all reference each other but nothing else points to them, they're still garbage — just connected garbage. The collector identifies and frees these cycles as one group.",
      "title": "Circular References Get Handled"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Tudo começa quando um fóton de luz bate na clorofila do Fotossistema II. A energia do fóton é tão intensa que arranca um elétron do lugar — é como um bilhar cósmico, a bola de luz derruba outra bola (o elétron) da posição de repouso.",
      "title": "A Batida da Luz no Fotossistema II"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aquele elétron agora está excitado, vibrando de energia. Ele não consegue ficar ali — salta para uma molécula receptora próxima. Pense em uma criança em um trampolim: a energia a impulsiona para cima, e ela tem que ir para algum lugar.",
      "title": "O Elétron Dispara para Frente"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aqui vem a mágica: enquanto o elétron salta de molécula em molécula (como em um jogo de pinball molecular), bombeia prótons para dentro da bolsa do tilacoide. Cada salto do elétron desloca um próton. A bolsa fica cada vez mais cheia de prótons positivos.",
      "title": "Construindo o Gradiente de Prótons"
    },
    {
      "text": "O elétron chega ao Fotossistema I, que está esperando. Outro fóton o pega, re-energiza, e o lança novamente. É como dar uma segunda volta de trampolim — o elétron sai ainda mais energizado para as próximas estações.",
      "title": "A Segunda Descarga do Fotossistema I"
    },
    {
      "text": "O elétron super-energizado agora reduz o NADP+ em NADPH. Imagine NADP+ como um contenedor vazio — o elétron extra (com seu energético passageiro) cai dentro, transformando-o em NADPH, a molécula que vai carregar essa energia para o próximo ato.",
      "title": "Carregando o Caminhão NADPH"
    },
    {
      "text": "Enquanto isso, a bolsa do tilacoide está bloqueada por prótons. Eles constroem pressão, como água atrás de uma represa. A diferença de concentração entre dentro e fora cria um gradiente poderoso — prótons querem sair desesperadamente.",
      "title": "A Pressão Acumula"
    },
    {
      "text": "A ATP sintase é como uma turbina de usina hidrelétrica. Os prótons não conseguem sair direto — têm que passar por essa turbina. Enquanto fluem, giram a turbina molecular, que usa essa rotação para colar um fosfato no ADP, transformando em ATP.",
      "title": "A Turbina Molecular Gira"
    },
    {
      "text": "ATP e NADPH saem da reação luminosa como dois pacotes de energia, prontos para viajar. O ATP é o dinheiro rápido (energia imediata), o NADPH é o cheque pós-datado (poder redutor para reações futuras). Ambos agora vão alimentar as reações escuras.",
      "title": "Os Prêmios Saem Carregados"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagina un mercado de frutas por la mañana: vendedores llegan con sus canastos listos para vender, compradores entran con sus billeteras dispuestos a comprar. Pero aquí está el problema — ¿a qué precio comienza el día? Nadie lo ha decidido aún. El mercado está en blanco, esperando que algo lo ponga en movimiento.",
      "title": "El Mercado Despierta sin Precio"
    },
    {
      "text": "El vendedor mira su canasto y piensa: \"Si vendo a $10 por kilo, traería más frutas mañana.\" Una compradora ve el precio y dice: \"A $10 está muy caro, compraré menos.\" Cada persona responde al precio que ve — pero ¿quién lo puso ahí primero? Alguien debe arriesgarse y gritar un número.",
      "title": "El Primer Grito de Precio"
    },
    {
      "text": "Un vendedor audaz grita: \"¡Frutas a $8 por kilo!\" Mira alrededor. ¿Qué pasa? Algunos compradores avanzan, otros se quedan quietos, muchos vendedores murmuran. El precio fue demasiado bajo — los vendedores ven que sus ganancias se evaporan. Alguien debe cambiar la propuesta.",
      "title": "El Precio Inicial Genera Reacciones"
    },
    {
      "text": "\"¡Espera!\" dice otro vendedor. \"Yo las vendo a $12.\" Ahora los compradores se detienen — demasiado caro. Solo compran lo mínimo. Pero observa lo que sucede: cuando el precio sube, los vendedores quieren traer más frutas, pero los compradores quieren menos. Se forma una tensión.",
      "title": "La Tensión Comienza a Aparecer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Mientras vendedores y compradores negocian, algo fascinante ocurre: los precios no suben ni bajan al azar. Cada pequeño cambio provoca una reacción. Menos demanda → vendedores bajan precio. Menos oferta → compradores suben precio. Es como un péndulo que oscila, buscando algo.",
      "title": "El Péndulo Busca Estabilidad"
    },
    {
      "text": "Finalmente, un vendedor grita: \"¡$10 por kilo!\" Y ocurre lo mágico: los compradores que llegan compran exactamente lo que los vendedores trajeron. Nadie se va con frutas sin vender, nadie se va sin poder comprar. El mercado respira — ha encontrado su ritmo.",
      "title": "El Punto de Equilibrio Emerge"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pero mira lo invisible que sucede: ningún supervisor ordenó este precio, ninguna autoridad lo impuso. Surgió de miles de decisiones pequeñas — compradores preguntando \"¿Vale la pena?\", vendedores calculando \"¿Ganaré lo suficiente?\" El precio es el resultado de sus conversaciones sin fin.",
      "title": "El Descubrimiento Sin Director"
    },
    {
      "text": "Si un nuevo distribuidor llega con frutas de mejor calidad, los compradores quieren más. El precio sube naturalmente porque hay mayor demanda. Si llegan muchos vendedores nuevos con frutas iguales, la oferta crece y el precio baja. El mercado está siempre reacomodándose, redescubriendo el precio.",
      "title": "El Precio Se Ajusta con Cambios"
    },
    {
      "text": "Observa algo crucial: el precio de equilibrio no es el que cualquiera querría. Los vendedores preferirían precios más altos, los compradores precios más bajos. Pero el equilibrio es el único precio donde ambos grupos pueden transaccionar sin sobras ni escasez. Es un compromiso que emerge naturalmente.",
      "title": "Un Compromiso Natural Emerge"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando el mercado cierra al atardecer, el precio de $10 por kilo se ha convertido en información compartida. Los productores rurales lo saben, los restaurantes lo saben, incluso los compradores de mañana lo esperarán. El descubrimiento de precio conectó a todos sin que nadie tuviera que anunciarlo.",
      "title": "El Precio Se Convierte en Información"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A stray neutron from cosmic rays or natural decay crashes into a U-235 nucleus. The nucleus absorbs this particle like a ball catching a stone — suddenly unstable and vibrating violently from the impact.",
      "title": "The Collision That Starts Everything"
    },
    {
      "text": "The wobbly nucleus splits into two smaller fragments, and like a stretched rubber band snapping, energy explodes outward. But the real trigger for a chain reaction hasn't fired yet.",
      "title": "The Nucleus Tears Apart"
    },
    {
      "text": "As the nucleus shatters, it releases 2-3 brand new neutrons — fast-moving particles shot in different directions. These aren't trapped; they're free to find the next nucleus.",
      "title": "Neutrons Spray Outward"
    },
    {
      "text": "Those ejected neutrons speed through the material. If they hit other U-235 nuclei, the process repeats — each collision triggers another fission, releasing more neutrons.",
      "title": "The Chain Begins to Form"
    },
    {
      "text": "Watch what happens next: one neutron causes one fission (2-3 new neutrons). Those hit nuclei, creating 4-9 neutrons. The number doubles or triples with each generation — exponential growth.",
      "title": "Exponential Explosion"
    },
    {
      "text": "In a nuclear bomb, this happens in millionths of a second. Billions of fissions release unimaginable energy all at once, with no way to stop the cascade.",
      "title": "Runaway Reaction"
    },
    {
      "text": "In a reactor, control rods made of neutron-absorbing material slide into the fuel. They catch the loose neutrons like a net, preventing them from hitting new nuclei and slowing the reaction.",
      "title": "Controlled by Absorption"
    },
    {
      "text": "Operators adjust how deep the rods sink. Pull them out slightly — more neutrons escape, reaction speeds up. Push deeper — more neutrons get caught, reaction slows. It's a balancing act.",
      "title": "Tuning the Rate"
    },
    {
      "text": "Below the critical point, neutrons are absorbed faster than new fissions occur — the reaction fizzles out. Above it, new fissions outpace losses — the chain accelerates uncontrollably.",
      "title": "The Critical Threshold"
    },
    {
      "text": "Energy from fissions heats water to steam, which spins turbines and generates electricity. The heat also triggers more fissions nearby — the process feeds itself steadily if controlled right.",
      "title": "From Chain Reaction to Power"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A magnet moves toward a coil of wire, and the magnetic field lines start flooding through the loops. Watch as more and more field lines punch through each turn of the coil — this increasing density is the trigger. The conductor hasn't moved, but the field passing through it is changing moment by moment.",
      "title": "The Field Starts Moving"
    },
    {
      "text": "As the magnetic field intensifies through the coil, the free electrons inside the wire feel a push. They sense the changing magnetic environment and start to shift. This invisible force — not gravity, not touch — nudges the charge carriers into motion, like a crowd responding to a wave.",
      "title": "Electrons Feel the Shift"
    },
    {
      "text": "The electrons don't just move randomly. The direction of their motion follows Lenz's law — they flow in a direction that opposes the change causing them. If the field strengthens downward, electrons move to create a field pointing upward, fighting back against the increase.",
      "title": "Electrons Resist the Change"
    },
    {
      "text": "As electrons stream through the wire, they create a moving flow of charge — an electric current. This current didn't come from a battery; it was born directly from the changing magnetic field. The current is strongest when the field changes fastest, weakest when it changes slowly.",
      "title": "Current Emerges from Motion"
    },
    {
      "text": "If you connect a light bulb or meter to the coil, electricity flows through it. The current keeps running as long as the magnet keeps moving and the field keeps changing. The instant you stop moving the magnet, the field stabilizes and the current dies.",
      "title": "Energy Flows Where There's Change"
    },
    {
      "text": "Now reverse direction — pull the magnet away from the coil. The field lines thin out, the flux decreases, and electrons respond by flowing the opposite direction. Same process, but the current reverses. This is why generators alternate: push and pull create alternating current.",
      "title": "Reversing Creates AC Motion"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push the magnet faster, and notice the current grows stronger. Slow it down, and the current weakens. This is Faraday's principle in action: the rate of change matters more than the final state. Rapid flux change = large induced EMF = strong current.",
      "title": "Speed Amplifies the Effect"
    },
    {
      "text": "If you coil the wire into multiple loops instead of a single turn, watch what happens: each loop experiences the same flux change, and all those loops add their induced voltages together. Ten loops don't just feel the field ten times — they generate ten times the EMF.",
      "title": "Loops Stack the Voltage"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Veja um substrato flutuando no meio aquoso, chocando-se aleatoriamente com moléculas ao seu redor. Ele precisa ser transformado, mas sozinho, as moléculas não têm energia suficiente para quebrar suas ligações. É aqui que a enzima entra em cena.",
      "title": "O Substrato Procura Seu Caminho"
    },
    {
      "text": "A enzima está flutuando nas proximidades, seu sítio ativo como uma fechadura esperando a chave certa. Quando o substrato passa perto, as forças intermoleculares (hidrofóbicas, eletrostáticas) começam a atraí-lo. É um reconhecimento molecular.",
      "title": "O Encontro Acontece"
    },
    {
      "text": "O substrato encaixa perfeitamente no sítio ativo — como uma chave entrando em uma fechadura. Ligações fracas (pontes de hidrogênio, interações de van der Waals) fixam o substrato no lugar, formando o complexo enzima-substrato. A reação está prestes a começar.",
      "title": "O Encaixe Perfeito"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aqui acontece a mágica: a enzima distorce ligeiramente a estrutura do substrato, esticando e tensionando suas ligações químicas. Essa deformação é como comprimir uma mola — coloca o substrato em um estado pronto para reagir, reduzindo drasticamente a energia que ele precisa investir.",
      "title": "A Distorção Estratégica"
    },
    {
      "text": "Com o substrato já esticado pela enzima, a barreira energética cai dramaticamente. Reações que levariam horas ou dias sem a enzima agora acontecem em milissegundos. A reação prossegue — ligações quebram e novas ligações se formam rapidamente.",
      "title": "A Reação Ocorre"
    },
    {
      "text": "Os produtos da reação são formados, mas não se encaixam bem no sítio ativo — a forma do sítio foi otimizada para o substrato, não para o produto. As ligações fracas se rompem naturalmente e o produto é liberado, flutuando para longe.",
      "title": "Os Produtos Saem"
    },
    {
      "text": "A enzima está intacta e inalterada, seu sítio ativo limpo e pronto. Milissegundos depois, outro substrato se aproxima e o ciclo recomeça. Uma única enzima pode catalisar centenas de reações por segundo — uma máquina molecular incansável.",
      "title": "A Máquina Se Reseta"
    },
    {
      "text": "Se a enzima não estivesse ali, o substrato precisaria ser aquecido a temperaturas extremas ou colocado em condições químicas agressivas para superar a barreira energética. Com a enzima, tudo acontece na temperatura do corpo, em segundos. É a diferença entre um reação impossível e uma vida.",
      "title": "Por que Enzimas Mudam o Jogo"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Conectas una batería a dos electrodos metálicos sumergidos en una solución de agua y sal. La batería comienza a empujar electrones por el circuito — es como abrir una compuerta de energía. Ese flujo de electrones es lo que fuerza todo lo demás.",
      "title": "La Batería Abre la Compuerta"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los electrones viajan por el cable hacia el cátodo (electrodo negativo). Allí se acumulan como agua detrás de una presa, creando una carga negativa que atrae fuertemente a los iones positivos en la solución — los cationes comienzan su marcha.",
      "title": "Electrones Inundan el Cátodo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Al mismo tiempo, los electrones salen del ánodo (electrodo positivo), dejando tras de sí un \"vacío\" de carga negativa. Es como abrir una compuerta por el otro lado — esa ausencia atrae a los iones negativos de la solución hacia el ánodo.",
      "title": "El Ánodo se Vuelve Hambriento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los cationes aceleran hacia el cátodo negativo, atraídos como metal hacia un imán. Cuando llegan, reciben electrones del electrodo y se transforman en átomos neutros — de cargas positivas a átomos completos. La reacción de reducción sucede aquí.",
      "title": "Los Cationes Reciben Electrones"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los aniones se precipitan hacia el ánodo positivo, también atraídos por la carga opuesta. Al llegar, ceden electrones al electrodo — pierden electrones y se transforman. Esta reacción de oxidación libera electrones que vuelven a la batería.",
      "title": "Los Aniones Pierden Electrones"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aquí está el truco: los electrones que cedieron los aniones regresan por el cable externo a la batería, que los recarga y vuelve a empujarlos hacia el cátodo. Es un ciclo continuo — un carrusel de energía que mantiene las reacciones en marcha.",
      "title": "El Circuito Se Cierra"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los nuevos átomos formados en los electrodos pueden hacer cosas que normalmente no suceden: cobre puro puede depositarse en el cátodo, o gases como oxígeno e hidrógeno pueden burbujear desde la solución. La electrólisis fuerza cambios químicos que la naturaleza no haría sola.",
      "title": "Productos Nuevos Emergen"
    },
    {
      "text": "Si detienes la batería, el flujo de electrones se detiene, los iones dejan de moverse y las reacciones se congelan. Sin energía externa empujando constantemente, la electrólisis no puede existir — depende completamente de ese empujón eléctrico continuo.",
      "title": "Sin Batería, Todo Se Detiene"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "The central bank announces a rate cut, and instantly, banks face a decision point: with lower borrowing costs at the central bank's window, should they hold cash or deploy it? This single announcement ripples outward — the game is now afoot.",
      "title": "The Rate Cut Triggers Bank Behavior"
    },
    {
